</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FC30FBCEBCE1CB3B" box="[913,980,1059,1085]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Carex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FC30FBCEBCE1CB3B" box="[913,980,1059,1085]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">Carex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FC40FBCFBBA5CB3B" author="Gaumann, E." box="[993,1168,1058,1085]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" refId="ref19274" refString="Gaumann, E. (1959) Die Rostpilze Mitteleuropas. Buchdruckerei Bucheler Co, Bern, Germany." type="book" year="1959">Gäumann 1959</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FB39FBCFBA1CCB3A" author="Harada, Y." box="[1176,1321,1058,1084]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" pagination="375 - 380" refId="ref19293" refString="Harada, Y. (1977) Puccinia caricis-circaearum, sp. nov., heteroecious Carex rust fungus from Japan. Transactions of Mycological Society of Japan 18: 375 - 380." type="journal article" year="1977">Harada 1977</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FA93FBCFBE15CB66" author="Kakishima, M. &amp; Sato, S." pageId="19" pageNumber="240" pagination="403 - 408" refId="ref20442" refString="Kakishima, M. &amp; Sato, S. (1983) Puccinia kawakamiensis, a new caricicolous rust, produces the aecial state on Circaea erubescens. Transactions of Mycological Society of Japan 24: 403 - 408." type="journal article" year="1983">Kakishima &amp; Sato 1983</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FE8EFBABBD12CB66" author="Hiratsuka, N. &amp; Sato, S. &amp; Katsuya, K. &amp; Kakishima, M. &amp; Hiratsuka, Y. &amp; Kaneko, S. &amp; Ono, Y. &amp; Sato, T. &amp; Harada, Y. &amp; Hiratsuka, T. &amp; Nakayama, K." box="[303,551,1094,1121]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" refId="ref19488" refString="Hiratsuka, N., Sato, S., Katsuya, K., Kakishima, M., Hiratsuka, Y., Kaneko, S., Ono, Y., Sato, T., Harada, Y., Hiratsuka, T. &amp; Nakayama, K. (1992) The rust flora of Japan. Tsukuba-shuppankai, Tsukuba, Japan." type="book" year="1992">
Hiratsuka 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FE07FBAABEEECB66" box="[422,475,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">et al</emphasis>
. 1992
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FD95FBABBDD2CB67" author="Azbukina, Z. M." box="[564,743,1094,1121]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" refId="ref18941" refString="Azbukina, Z. M. (2005) Rust fungi, Cryptogamic plants, fungi and mosses of the Russian Far East, vol. 5. Dalnauka, Vladivostok, Russia." type="book" year="2005">Azbukina 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FD57FBABBC06CB67" author="Azbukina, Z. M." box="[758,819,1094,1121]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" refId="ref18975" refString="Azbukina, Z. M. (2015) Definitorium fungorum Rossiae, Ordo Pucciniales 1. Dal'nauka, Vladivostok, Russia." type="book" year="2015">2015</bibRefCitation>
). The morphological characteristics of the above three species are similar to each other, but different in the positions of urediniospore germ pores. Uredinia are very rare in the specimen on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FEBBFB62BE68CBAF" box="[282,349,1167,1193]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Carex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FEBBFB62BE68CBAF" box="[282,349,1167,1193]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">Carex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in this clade and the urediniospore germ pores are unclear. However, morphological characteristics of spermogonial, aecial, and telial stages are identical with the descriptions of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FBAFFB5EBBD4CBCA" box="[1038,1249,1203,1228]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="circaeae-caricis">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FBAFFB5EBBD4CBCA" box="[1038,1249,1203,1228]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">P. circaeae-caricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FAAEFB5FBA9ECBCA" author="Hasler, A." box="[1295,1451,1202,1228]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" pagination="345 - 357" refId="ref19388" refString="Hasler, A. (1930) Beitrage zur Kenntnis einiger Carex - Puccinien. Annales Mycologici 28: 345 - 357." type="journal article" year="1930">Hasler (1930)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FF16FB3BBE4DCBF7" author="Gaumann, E." box="[183,376,1238,1265]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" refId="ref19274" refString="Gaumann, E. (1959) Die Rostpilze Mitteleuropas. Buchdruckerei Bucheler Co, Bern, Germany." type="book" year="1959">Gäumann (1959)</bibRefCitation>
, athough the shape and size of aeciospores and teliospores are slightly different among the three species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FF46FB17BEC3CA12" author="Kakishima, M. &amp; Sato, S." box="[231,502,1274,1300]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" pagination="403 - 408" refId="ref20442" refString="Kakishima, M. &amp; Sato, S. (1983) Puccinia kawakamiensis, a new caricicolous rust, produces the aecial state on Circaea erubescens. Transactions of Mycological Society of Japan 24: 403 - 408." type="journal article" year="1983">Kakishima &amp; Sato 1983</bibRefCitation>
) and the aeciospores and teliospores are small. This species is phylogenetically close to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FF04FAF2BEAECA3E" box="[165,411,1310,1336]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="caricis-atractylodis">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FF04FAF2BEAECA3E" box="[165,411,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">P. caricis-atractylodis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FE70FAF2BD6FCA3E" baseAuthorityName="Kakishima &amp; Sato" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[465,602,1311,1336]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="vaginatae">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FE70FAF2BD6FCA3E" box="[465,602,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">P. vaginatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but distinct from them. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FCCFFAF3BB53CA3F" author="Hylander, N. &amp; Jorstad, I. &amp; Nannfeldt, J. A." box="[878,1126,1310,1337]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" pagination="1 - 102" refId="ref19665" refString="Hylander, N., Jorstad, I. &amp; Nannfeldt, J. A. (1953) Enumeratio Uredinearum Scandinavicarum. Opera Botany 1: 1 - 102." type="journal article" year="1953">
Hylander 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FC7CFAF2BB3BCA3E" box="[989,1038,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">et al</emphasis>
. (1953)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC0FFD6FB3BFAF3BA6CCA3F" author="Azbukina, Z. M." box="[1178,1369,1310,1337]" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" refId="ref18941" refString="Azbukina, Z. M. (2005) Rust fungi, Cryptogamic plants, fungi and mosses of the Russian Far East, vol. 5. Dalnauka, Vladivostok, Russia." type="book" year="2005">Azbukina (2005)</bibRefCitation>
treated this species as a variety of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FE62FAAEBD0BCA5A" box="[451,574,1347,1372]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="caricina">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FE62FAAEBD0BCA5A" box="[451,574,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">P. caricina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this species is phylogenetically far from 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FBF0FAAEBBF9CA5A" box="[1105,1228,1347,1372]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="caricina">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FBF0FAAEBBF9CA5A" box="[1105,1228,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">P. caricina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC0FFD6FB58FAAEBA56CA5A" box="[1273,1379,1347,1372]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="19" pageNumber="240" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="caricis">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC0FFD6FB58FAAEBA56CA5A" box="[1273,1379,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">P. caricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation id="13512A00FFC0FFD6FADFFAAFBFA3CA86" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1761,1783]" captionTargetBox="[138,1449,389,1737]" captionTargetId="figure-110@7.[138,1449,389,1737]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Phylogenetic tree of specimens on Cyperaceae and related host plants constructed by MP method based on ITS+28S regions of rDNA. Bootstrap values of MP and ML are followed by the Bayesian posterior probabilities (Bpp) on the nodes in the topology.Asterisk (*) represents bootstrap values or Bpp less than 50% in the topology. Sample data are shown with voucher specimen number or GenBank accession number, and host plant. Sequence data determined in this study are shown in color. Teliospore shapes are shown in each clade detected, and new species are shown by asterisk (*) on clades. 0, I: Spermogonial and aecial host genus. Asterisk (*) on host plants: Spermogonial and aecial host plants." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6416749" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6416749/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) and, therefore, this species should be treated as an independent species. This is the first record of this species in 
<collectingCountry id="F37D7615FFC0FFD6FF29FA67BFFACAA2" box="[136,207,1418,1444]" name="China" pageId="19" pageNumber="240">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
